---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About">
  <article class="container-x py-14">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-3">About</p>
    <h1 class="text-4xl">The Examine.com of the whole body.</h1>
    <div class="prose-materia mt-6 text-fg">
      <p>
        The answer to “what can I take for this?” is scattered across products that never talk to
        each other. Beautiful anatomy apps show you the body but say nothing about remedies.
        Rigorous supplement databases grade the evidence but have no sense of <em>where</em> in the
        body anything matters. Interaction checkers that include herbs sit behind clinical paywalls.
      </p>
      <p>Materia joins them.</p>
      <p>
        Explore a layered human body, click any part, and follow it down to the conditions that
        affect it and the herbs, supplements, chemicals, and drugs that have been studied for them —
        each graded by the strength of the research, linked to the studies, and checked for
        interactions. It’s a connected reference: body → condition → remedy → active compound →
        mechanism → study, traversable from any direction.
      </p>
      <h2>Our promises</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ad-free.</strong> No banner ads, no pop-ups, no sponsored placements.</li>
        <li><strong>We sell nothing.</strong> No supplement store, no affiliate links.</li>
        <li>
          <strong>Every claim is graded and cited.</strong> If we can’t cite it, we don’t publish it.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We aggregate, we don’t claim.</strong> Materia summarizes and links to external sources —
          health agencies, Cochrane, peer-reviewed studies. The authority is theirs; our job is to gather
          and grade it honestly.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Honest about uncertainty.</strong> “Insufficient evidence” is a valid, common answer.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Materia is educational and not a substitute for professional care. See our
        <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> for how we grade evidence, and our
        <a href="/disclaimer">disclaimer</a> before you act on anything here.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
